<TEXT>
the bush administration says it wont mind if 
congress forgives interest and penalties on an obscure liquor tax 
that many tavern and restaurant owners on the deadbeat list say 
theyve never heard of 
a treasury department official told a house ways and means 
subcommittee thursday that the administration does not oppose a 
house plan to erase interest and penalties that accrued before july 
on the 123yearold tax 
but kenneth w gideon assistant treasury secretary for tax 
policy stopped short of endorsing a waiver of the tax debts 
themselves 
protests over the tax grew after a pennsylvania elks lodge got a 
9776 bill last year for 50 years of nonpayment and a california 
pizza shop owner received a 2911 bill four weeks ago 
owners of both establishments said they had never heard of the 
special occupational tax on liquor retailers 
about 600000 beer wine and distilled spirits dealers who sell 
directly to the public must pay the annual tax which was increased 
in january 1988 from 54 to 250 per retailer 
accompanying the increase has been a vigorous enforcement effort 
by the bureau of alcohol tobacco and firearms which took 
responsibility for collections from the internal revenue service in 
1986 
although we continue to believe that taxpayer amnesty programs 
are generally inappropriate this case involves a tax that for 
years before 1987 was insignificant and not well publicized 
gideon said in prepared testimony before the subcommittee on select 
revenue measures 
it appears that noncompliance in years before 1987 was due to 
the fact that many taxpayers were simply not aware of the tax 
there is no evidence that dealers were attempting to avoid the 
tax 
only about 40 percent of retailers paid before 1987 gideon 
said adding that the compliance rate has risen to 80 percent 
