<TEXT>
advisers are recommending that energy 
secretary james d watkins order a longer test period before 
opening the nations first permanent dump for longlived 
radioactive waste from nuclear weapons plants 
the proposed changes if accepted by watkins would force the 
energy department to arrange temporary storage of nuclear 
wastes for a much longer period than planned said leonard slosky 
one of five members of a blueribbon advisory group watkins 
impaneled two months ago to study the problem 
watkins already is having trouble persuading any of seven 
selected states washington idaho nevada colorado new mexico 
tennessee and south carolina to store extra nuclear weapons waste 
for about 2 years starting in april 
the waste had been going to idaho but gov cecil andrus banned 
further shipments sept 1 watkins had hoped to have a permanent 
dump opened in new mexico by now but environmental and other 
problems have delayed it indefinitely 
watkins told congress earlier this month that he expected to 
start operations demonstration of the permanent waste dump 
known as the waste isolation pilot plant by september 1992 that 
would involve loading shipping unloading depositing and 
retrieving drums of the nuclear waste to demonstrate that the 
system the first of its kind in the world can work safely 
the plant is near carlsbad nm 
on tuesday however four of the five advisory panel members 
told watkins in a private meeting that the operational testing 
should be put off for at least four years slosky said thursday 
that would mean the dump could take only a small amounts of 
waste equal to about 1 percent of its capacity for the next four 
or five years said slosky an environmental scientist based in 
denver 
robert bishop representing a nuclear industry group said he 
was the lone dissenter on the advisory group he added however 
that all members agreed the energy departments plans for opening 
the repository are probably too optimistic 
rep david skaggs dcolo said in an interview that the 
advisory groups conclusions would intensify the political pressure 
on watkins to solve the waste problem 
it removes any pretense that the operational testing was 
anything other than a device for getting waste into the ground 
to relieve the waste storage problem skaggs said 
the panel wrote no joint report but instead the members 
presented their own recommendations in separate papers for watkins 
on tuesday slosky and bishop said in telephone interviews 
energy department officials familiar with the reports did not 
return a reporters phone calls thursday the department has not 
published the papers 
an environmental group said in response to the advisory panels 
recommendations that watkins faced further delays and political 
fights over the dump 
for political and technical reasons its not going to open 
any time soon said elizabeth kassen a senior lawyer for the 
environmental defense fund 
the panel members also told watkins they saw serious management 
problems that should be corrected before the dump is opened 
in his written report to watkins slosky stressed the importance 
of completing tests to show the repository can handle the wastes 
and remove them in the first few years if major problems are 
discovered 
however given the current degree of uncertainty regarding the 
ability of the repository to meet regulatory requirements it is 
not prudent to transport large quantities of waste to the site 
he wrote 
