the us congress wants to lend a helping hand 
to its fledgling counterpart in poland by providing the hardware 
and software of westernstyle democracy 
the senate late thursday approved a resolution that will send a 
team of congressional experts to poland to study the needs of the 
newly formed parliament they will come up with an aid package that 
includes everything from telephones and typewriters to training in 
how to write laws 
while were talking about the bigger issues of loan 
stabilization of economic reform of food aid it is quite 
appropriate for congress to give this as a first gift of 
democracy said sen pete domenici a sponsor of the initiative 
polands first open elections since before world war ii held in 
april gave the country its first noncommunistdominated 
government in four decades but the newly elected lawmakers many 
of them workers with no previous experience in government soon 
found they had inherited an empty shell of a legislature domenici 
said 
used only to rubberstamp decisions of previous communist 
governments the parliament has no mechanism for drafting laws or 
even keeping track of laws already on the books there is no 
organizational structure like the us congress system of 
committees there are no workable rules of procedure for the sejm 
the lower house or the newly created senate 
domenici and a group of former us lawmakers went to poland in 
september to meet with a select group of the new legislators 
including members of the nowdominant solidarity party and other 
parties 
the new elected officials are bright able and motivated he 
said one is a manager at a tractor factory another a physician at 
the gdansk shipyards another a college professor and another a 
union leader the group probably had more experience in organizing 
protests than in governing many had spent time in jail under the 
old regime 
we thought we were going to talk about economics how you 
create a capitalist system domenici rnm said in an 
interview they were interested in that but they really wanted 
to know how to run a parliament 
it boiled down to basics how do you gather information how 
do you get sufficient informationgathering equipment to keep track 
of your laws they have no library system no simple computer 
system no copying machines they dont have a system of producing 
reports 
so while we talked about a lot of philosophical things 
they need some of the basic equipment that we take for granted 
domenici said when the group which included former sens walter 
