<TEXT>
legislation is heading to president bush that 
will increase disaster payments to farmers who planted replacement 
crops after their wheat and cotton failed because of bad weather 
this year 
the senate and house gave final approval to the measure 
thursday and republican leader bob dole rkan predicted bush 
would sign the bill pushed through by farmstate lawmakers in a 
bipartisan effort 
farmers had a legitimate gripe that producers who moved 
quickly to plant a second crop on failed acres shouldnt be 
penalized when it came time to qualify for federal disaster aid 
dole said 
the measure will change the way disaster assistance payments are 
calculated for farmers who planted a replacement crop after 
drought flooding and other extreme weather destroyed their first 
crops 
lawmakers have complained that an agriculture department formula 
will penalize those producers and in some instances mean farmers 
could receive no disaster payments even though they earned little 
or no profit on their second crops 
winter wheat and cotton farmers will be particularly affected 
because many planted grain sorghum and soybeans after their initial 
crops failed 
the problem stems from a nearly 900 million disaster relief 
package enacted in august in an effort to prevent farmers from 
reaping double benefits the law required usda to reduce assistance 
payments to farmers by the value of any crop that replaced one 
ruined by bad weather 
congress didnt spell out how to determine the replacement crop 
value leaving that to usda the agency decided to deduct 75 
percent of the gross value of the replacement crop from the 
disaster payment a farmer would have otherwise received for losses 
on his first crop 
lawmakers reacted angrily contending that usdas formula was 
arbitrary and failed to account for regiontoregion differences in 
production costs 
under the legislation that system would be modified 
farmers would have no payment reductions if their replacement 
crops failed to produce more than 50 percent of the county average 
yield those farmers harvesting more than that amount would have 
usdas deduction applied only on the value of their replacement 
crop above the 50 percent yield threshold 
in addition replacement crop deductions would be applied only 
against disaster assistance earned on acres actually replanted 
farmers would receive smaller payments without those acreage 
offsets 
</TEXT>
