<TEXT>
president bush vetoed the district of 
columbias 34 annual spending package today because it permitted 
use of city tax dollars for medicaidfunded abortions 
bushs veto which had been widely expected was announced by 
the white house when the president arrived in costa rica for a 
twoday visit 
the veto came two days after the house sustained bushs veto of 
a labor health and education spending bill that also permitted use 
of medicaid funds for abortions for poor women made pregnant 
through rape or incest 
the veto came despite protests from city officials that the 
districts antidrug efforts would be imperiled unless the spending 
package was approved 
included in the bill was 32 million in extra federal money to 
pay for the hiring of 700 extra police officers extra judges and a 
variety of schoolbased drug education and prevention programs 
congress approved the anticrime package to help the capital 
battle its record homicide rate and drugrelated crime wave the 
bill also included a payment of 435 million to make up for local 
tax revenue lost on federally owned property 
abortionrights advocates and local government officials also 
complained that if bush vetoed the bill he would be exerting 
unfair influence over the citys legislative affairs 
the abortion debate began in july when the house voted to allow 
the district to use its own tax money to pay for medicaidfunded 
abortions at the time lawmakers said the city was given the right 
because of last summers supreme court ruling that granted states 
great latitude in regulating abortions 
the city traditionally has funded abortions for lowincome women 
in last years budget antiabortion forces in congress 
succeeded in barring the city from using its own taxes for any type 
of abortion 
city officials said earlier this week that they do not expect 
congress to muster the twothirds vote necessary to override bushs 
veto in both the house and senate 
