the senate today approved and sent to 
president bush legislation raising to 124875 the ceiling on home 
mortgages insured by the federal government in highcost housing 
markets 
the measure part of a 67 billion spending bill for housing 
veterans environmental and space programs was approved by an 846 
vote the house approved the same bill wednesday 
voting against the bill were sens william armstrong rcolo 
alan j dixon dill jesse helms rnc gordon humphrey 
rnh steve symms ridaho and william v roth rdel 
currently the ceiling on mortgages insured by the federal 
housing administration is 101250 an amount below the median 
price of homes in 18 states and the district of columbia 
proponents said raising the fha mortgage ceiling will help tens 
of thousands of young families cope with higher real estate prices 
opponents however contended the higher ceiling will only 
deepen the exposure of the fha to losses that will have to be made 
up by taxpayers if a large number of the loans turn sour the fha 
lost 42 billion last year in loan defaults 
the bill provides 124 billion for the national aeronautics and 
space administration including 18 billion for the planned space 
station in fiscal 1990 which began oct 1 
it also makes available 56 billion for the environmental 
protection agency 114 billion for veterans medical care and 
151 billion for housing programs 
