<TEXT>
several years ago otsego county sheriff 
martin ralph put his house his car and everything else he had in 
his wifes name he wants new yorks voters to do something about 
that on election day 
if she runs away tomorrow im homeless said ralph it 
shouldnt have to be that way 
ralph isnt having a fight with his wife and doesnt expect her 
to leave him instead hes battling to have what he believes is an 
onerous and antiquated provision of the state constitution 
eliminated 
that provision holds ralph and other state sheriffs personally 
liable for the acts of their departments and employees they are 
the only public officials in the state who face such potential 
personal liability for official acts 
when the states voters enter the ballot booth nov 7 theyll 
be able to decide on the fate of the provision with proposal 
number one an amendment 
should the amendment be approved residents can still sue the 
sheriff but they wont be able to get his home and car only money 
from the county 
peter kehoe executive director of the new york state sheriffs 
association said earlier this month there once was good reason for 
having the sheriffs held personally liable 
until the 1930s new york states sheriffs were unsalaried 
officials who got to keep all the fees collected by their offices 
the sheriff was essentially a private businessman said 
kehoe 
those fees could be substantial when a sheriff sold property to 
satisfy a court judgment he kept 5 percent of the selling price 
when he served a summons he got a fee 
they could become very wealthy said kehoe 
the job was so profitable that democrat al smith gave up his 
state assembly seat in 1915 to run for new york county sheriff 
having salted away between 50000 and 80000 in his twoyear 
term as sheriff according to a later biographer smith ran for and 
won the governorship in 1918 he later ran unsuccessfully for 
president 
the state law was later changed to make each sheriff a salaried 
employee of the county and to give the county all the fees 
salaries for sheriffs now range from 85000 a year in both 
westchester and monroe counties to the 25000 paid in rural 
schuyler county 
what wasnt changed was the constitutional provision making the 
sheriffs personally liable for official acts of their departments 
its a sword of damocles hanging over the sheriffs heads 
said kehoe fortunately the sword hasnt fallen 
so far the sheriffs have been lucky enough to have claims 
against them covered by the liability insurance thats carried by 
the counties kehoe said but insurance companies are questioning 
that coverage he said 
another problem said kehoe is the switch by many counties to 
selfinsurance a situation that could leave them without the legal 
authority to cover judgments against their sheriffs about 
onethird of counties have already become selfinsured he said 
its not a comfortable situation said kehoe the sheriffs 
are all worried about their families 
putnam county sheriff robert thoubboron said that while he 
