the outgoing un high commissioner for refugees 
said friday he resigned because it was increasingly difficult to do 
his job while the target of irresponsible attacks 
the resignation of jeanpierre hocke announced thursday at the 
united nations in new york followed allegations he misused a 
special un educational fund to subsidize firstclass air 
travel for himself 
hocke admitted he had flown first class a right reserved for 
the un secretarygeneral under stringent un austerity measures 
but denied any impropriety he said he had gone first class on some 
long intercontinental flights when he had a busy work schedule 
a danish statement said tuesday the account was opened for use 
by hockes danish predecessor poul hartling and that hocke showed 
a lack of judgment in believing assurances by a danish aide 
that he also could draw from it to cover travel expenses 
at denmarks request un secretarygeneral javier perez de 
cuellar ordered that an inquiry into the case be broadened 
at a news conference after returning to his native switzerland 
from new york hocke said his resignation does not reflect any 
sentiment of culpability on my part 
he said he did not feel pressured to resign and decided on his 
own to do so 
reading a statement hocke said the function of the high 
commissioner requires a total commitment and availability to act 
to convince and to galvanize 
that commitment was sapped by repeated and irresponsible 
attacks and destructive intentions of some people here and 
elsewhere he said without elaborating 
these were the considerations that led to my resignation 
which should not be seen as a withdrawal in the middle of the 
storm hocke added 
he said the agency will face a formidable challenge in the 
next few months when refugee protection and assistance will be more 
difficult than ever 
asked whether he was the victim of a campaign or realized he had 
made mistakes he said both 
i would never claim that i am free from making any mistakes 
he added 
