the manufacturer of an inhaler for asthmatics 
is recalling the medication after just one month on the market 
because of reports of coughing choking and gagging after use the 
food and drug administration said friday 
the drug is a new formula of a commonly prescribed metered dose 
inhaler alupent 
the fda said the medication is being removed from the us 
market because there has been a sharp increase in reports of 
adverse reactions with the reformulation 
coughing with a choking or gagging sensation has been the most 
commonly reported complaint with the reformulated alupent the 
agency said in a statement 
no deaths or hospitalizations have been reported and experts 
have not determined whether the new formula caused the current 
problems 
however boehringer ingelheim a connecticutbased company that 
is the major supplier of the drug said it will remove the 
reformulation the us market and bring its previous formula back 
patients should contact their doctors or pharmacists to 
determine if medication they are taking is included in the recall 
in no case should patients discontinue their current asthma 
drug treatment unless directed to do so by a physician said fda 
commissioner frank e young 
young said most patients using the reformulation have not 
experienced the side effects and discontinuing prescribed asthma 
therapies could result in lifethreatening or fatal asthma 
attacks 
