<TEXT>
the food and drug administration on friday 
completed regulations to guarantee that tampon absorbency labels 
mean the same thing regardless of what brand you buy 
today one brands regular or super may designate a much 
higher or lower absorbency than the same terms on another brand 
the agency said in a statement 
in the new system each term will correspond to a specific 
range of absorbency and manufacturers will use a standardized 
method to arrive at the absorbency for each type of tampon the 
statement said 
women use tampons which are sold in a range of thickness or 
absorbencies instead of sanitary napkins to control menstrual flow 
greater tampon absorbency has been associated with toxic shock 
syndrome a rare but sometimes fatal condition 
current tampon labeling requires a warning about the risks of 
tss and tampon use and a list of the symptons of the illness 
the new labels also must include an explanation of the 
absorbency range 
the standardization will permit purchasers to compare brands 
and health officials hope buy lower absorbency products to reduce 
their risk of toxic shock syndrome the fda added 
manufacturers have four months to comply with the new fda rule 
