<TEXT>
foreign businesses in moscow will reap the 
benefits of a drastically devalued ruble a state bank official 
said friday meaning they can pay staff and some other bills with 
cheaper rubles 
the soviet union on wednesday announced a devaluation of the 
ruble from 159 to 16 cents for foreign and soviet travelers cash 
exchanges starting nov 1 the higher rate will remain on 
commercial transactions 
foreign businessmen living in the soviet union also will receive 
the more favorable rate when changing cash said valery pekshev 
deputy chairman of the state bank 
asked at a news conference if businesses could use those funds 
to pay their soviet staff pekshev said if you have withdrawn 
cash from your foreign currency account you have the right to 
exchange your currency and nobodys going to control how you spend 
it 
however the change will have limited effect because the soviet 
government requires foreigners to use hard currency in paying many 
of their expenses including rent and office telephone bills most 
soviets working for foreigners also receive part of their salary in 
foreign currency 
pekshev said the ruble is being devalued because the official 
rate of 159 per ruble was not realistic he also cited a need 
to undercut the black market where tourists could receive up to 20 
times as many rubles for their convertible currency as in state 
bank outlets 
foreign travelers largest expenses for hotels and 
transportation must be paid in foreign currency to intourist the 
state tourist agency but pekshev said visitors may see a break 
here as well 
intourist will take the new exchange rate into account when 
negotiating new contracts with tour companies he said 
pekshev said the devaluation had been contemplated in summer but 
authorities did not want to disrupt the tourist season 
the limit on the amount of currency soviet citizens may exchange 
when traveling abroad will be raised so they will continue to 
receive about 300 each pekshev said but they will have to pay 10 
times as many rubles for that same small cache of spending money 
this will reduce the number of soviets traveling simply to buy 
coveted western goods in short supply at home pekshev said many 
soviets have been able to pay for their trips by bringing home such 
highly profitable items as a 2000 computer and selling it for 
50000 rubles 
we used to give them 318 for 200 rubles and they would make 
4000 to 5000 rubles off it he told the labor newspaper trud 
if the state takes not 200 rubles from them but 2000 it will 
be only fair 
although the ruble is still many years from becoming fully 
convertible pekshev said other adjustments are being made soviet 
exporters are due to receive a ruble bonus on their foreign 
currency earnings starting jan 1 
in addition a foreign currency auction among soviet enterprises 
is underway companies submitted closed bids to the vnesheconombank 
to buy or sell their foreign currency and next week officials 
expect to match them up 
gennady mazonov a senior researcher in the institute of world 
social system economics specializing in ruble convertibility said 
the devaluation was a happy unexpected surprise but said it 
should have gone as far as 10 cents to the ruble to compete with 
black market rates 
as it is he noted soviet tourists will still need more than 
300 each to travel abroad and there will be no effect on the 
unsatisfied hunger for foreign currency 
