<TEXT>
here is a text of the remarks of peggy say 
sister of terry anderson at a ceremony friday marking the 42nd 
birthday of the associated press chief middle east correspondent 
who has been held captive in lebanon since march 1985 
once again i have to grope for words to tell carmela laspada 
how deeply grateful i am for no greater loves sponsoring of yet 
another ceremony on behalf of terry anderson and the other 
hostages this is the 20th such ceremony and without carmelas 
devotion and dedication to our cause im afraid the hostage issue 
would have been forgotten long ago carmela for terry and the 
other hostages their families and friends i thank you 
to all of you who are participating and those attending this 
ceremony bless you terrys friends my friends members of the 
jctfta journalists committee to free terry anderson my ap 
family relatives especially my husband david and hostage 
family members you are my strength and without your support year 
after frustrating year i could not go on 
i know that each of you shares my pain as we gather here today 
to mark terrys 42nd birthday his fifth in captivity and to 
take part in this mass of hope 
i felt it was touchingly appropriate when carmela christened 
this particular ceremony a mass of hope i feel that hope is 
the common thread that binds us all together our capacity for hope 
is remarkable after enduring months and years of this terrible 
ordeal 
i have a plaque in my home that reads hope is not a way out 
it is a way through it is indeed it is that hope that motivates 
us to approach every ceremony in the belief that it will be the 
last it is hope that compels carmela to keep her plans for a 
welcome home party always at the ready 
despite years of crushed expectations false signs and broken 
dreams who among us is not ready to believe that today could be 
the day our miracle happens whose heart does not flutter when the 
telephone rings at odd hours hoping that this will be the call 
the one that brings our moment of joy hope is our willingness to 
believe against desperate odds that we will soon board a plane to 
wiesbaden for a reunion with our loved ones 
hope is what urges us to plan every day as if we might need to 
leave in haste no longterm projects no clothing long 
unlaundered no suitcase far from reach hope is what sustains us 
all especially those who must live in defiance of chains that bind 
them and cloths that blind them 
it is far easier for us their families and friends to maintain 
hope we have one another but for these remarkable men to live 
with hope in the face of such desperate conditions is a testament 
to their courage their faith and the dignity with which they 
exist 
it is with hope that i pray every day every night that 
something positive will emerge from the rubble and chaos we call 
lebanon that the hearts of their captors will be softened and our 
innocent men will be reunited with their families i live with the 
hope that the release of our hostages will in some way play a role 
in the healing of deep wounds between our arab brothers and 
ourselves 
it is my deepest hope that our hostages will not have suffered 
so much for so long in vain and for nothing i hope to see in my 
lifetime and for my children and my grandchildren a time of peace 
and reconciliation among all countries of the world for then with 
the psalmists we will see that kindness and truth shall meet 
justice and peace shall kiss truth shall spring out of the earth 
and justice shall look down from heaven 
i pray for our hostages and for us all that we never lose our 
capacity for hope that ability to believe in the potential promise 
of each new day some day soon please god our miracle will 
happen until then we will live as we always have in faith and 
hope thank you and god bless you all 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

