<TEXT>
as heavy equipment growls through the 
rubble of a collapsed oakland freeway that killed dozens in last 
weeks earthquake engineers friday said the freeways achilles 
heel appears more obvious each day 
while many factors contributed to interstate 880s destruction 
engineers say it appears that the bases of some of the vertical 
support columns snapped that allowed the upper lanes to slam down 
on the roadway below two separate engineering teams one from the 
university of california berkeley and the other from uc san diego 
reported 
neither team is ready to discount some of the other theories 
that surfaced in the days following the oct 17 collapse of the 
1mile section of the nimitz freeway 
and they added many factors probably were involved ranging 
from shaky ground to the peculiar way the 32yearold structure may 
have fallen in step with the seismic waves 
but the critical failure on the states oldest doubledecker 
freeway appears to have been at the point where many of the upper 
deck concrete columns attached to the lower deck jack p moehle 
an engineering professor and spokesman for the berkeley team said 
friday 
from the sketches ive seen it makes sense to me said nels 
roselund whose south pasadena engineering firm specializes in 
earthquakeproofing old structures 
the column joints which moehle said met construction standards 
when they were built might have held had they contained more 
reinforcing steel 
but engineers have more computer analysis and other testing to 
perform before they can be certain he and others said 
moehle added friday that despite assertions from state 
department of transportation engineers and others the onceswampy 
filled ground beneath the structure may have played a major role in 
its collapse by amplifying the quake 
we now have readings of ground motion under the freeway of 
an increase of threetenths g acceleration he said in contrast 
acceleration at nearby berkeley was only point zero nine 
moehle said a g is a unit of acceleration equal to the 
acceleration of gravity 
subsurface maps released by the transportion department earlier 
this week show that many of the structures 25 miles of steel 
pilings are in clay and none of them reach bedrock but caltrans 
chief structural engineer jim roberts said his geologists believe 
most pilings found sufficient anchor on a layer of hardpacked sand 
about 250 feet beneath the surface 
moehle criticized suggestions from critics that state engineers 
who oversaw the project 32 years ago should have required more 
steel in columns and that they should have bolstered the columns 
strength since then 
he said the work more than met prevailing construction standards 
of the time and moehle and others expressed doubt that engineers 
today could have anticipated the problems in the column joints 
unfortunately we only learn about earthquakes from 
earthquakes said clayton r giroux the retired state engineer 
who designed the structure 
roberts said that once the structure is razed at a cost of about 
10 million a new freeway eventually will be built at an estimated 
cost of 50 million to 100 million 
