moratorium on the use of high seas drift nets by the summer of 
1992 a state department official said friday 
the text has been circulated to a number of countries and we 
are now in a consultative process in the un said ed wolfe the 
state departments ambassador for oceans and fisheries 
under the proposed resolution the moratorium would take effect 
unless or until it is agreed based on scientific data that the 
unacceptable impact of such practices can be prevented and the 
conservation of the worlds living marine resources can be 
ensured 
thomas pickering us ambassador to the united nations is 
expected to formally introduce the resolution within the next few 
weeks 
the resolution notes that thousands of vessels use drift nets in 
the pacific atlantic and indian oceans and the mediterranean sea 
american fishermen say drift net vessels from japan taiwan and 
south korea have been snaring millions of us salmon in the north 
pacific and that fish runs in the washington state oregon and 
alaska have declined as a result of the illegal harvest 
the fishermen also insist the us tuna catch has fallen as a 
result of drift net fishing in the south pacific 
the smallmesh monofilament nets ostensibly used to catch 
squid snare anything they come in contact with and 
environmentalists have charged they kill thousands of marine 
mammals sea birds and other marine animals annually 
the nets can stretch more than 30 miles in length and on any 
given day can cover more than 30000 miles of ocean 
earlier this year the united states signed bilateral 
enforcement and monitoring agreements with taiwan korea and japan 
and the bush administration has been reluctant to seek an 
international ban on drift nets until those pacts expire next year 
