<TEXT>
when the stock market staged a brisk rally right 
after its scary slide on oct 13 most onlookers were relieved and 
impressed there evidently wasnt going to be a crash of 1989 after 
all 
but that performance failed to reassure some wall street 
analysts who found almost as much cause for concern in the rebound 
as they did in the drop 
after the dow jones industrial average fell more than 190 points 
on friday the 13th the optimists rallying cries began almost 
immediately 
the selloff was an aberration caused mainly by the 
spreading realization that the mergersandbuyouts boom of the past 
several years was coming under increasing strains 
the squeeze on takeover credit furthermore would ultimately 
prove beneficial by restoring investors attention to the 
traditional values that make the stock market go such as earnings 
and dividend growth 
besides everybody with memories of the crash of 1987 had 
learned that bargainhunters in big market drops could be 
handsomely rewarded when confidence was restored 
while any or all of these points may be valid the skeptics now 
say investors rushed to embrace them with an eagerness bordering 
on unreality 
just because monday oct 16 wasnt a repeat of black monday 
1987 doesnt mean that all is well contends joseph feshbach 
technical analyst at prudentialbache securities 
this isnt the worst of all possible investment worlds but it 
certainly isnt the best 
two years ago feshbach noted pessimism abounded and 
pessimism proved wrong today optimistic investors are comparing 
1989 with 1987 although the fundamentals and the internals of the 
market are very different this year from what they were two years 
ago 
those differences have been widely described as favorable for 
the market outlook now for instance priceearnings ratios of 
stocks are much lower now than the lofty levels they reached in the 
summer of 87 
similarly there appears much less danger now of an accelerating 
economy that would prompt the federal reserve to tighten credit 
but many analysts view the contrasts in sentiment between 
october 1987 and october 1989 much differently 
the crash of 87 was almost universally viewed as a fearsome 
event friday the 13th this october was dismissed by many as just a 
brief dizzy spell 
if the past is any guide significant market declines dont end 
in periods of eagerness to shop for bargains in stocks but rather 
when sentiment surrenders its enthusiasm and becomes scared in 
the words of justin mamis at cowan amp co 
the 1989 selloff and its aftermath prompted joseph barthel 
technical analyst at hopper soliday amp co to recommend that 
investors reduce their exposure to the stock market 
the burden of proof that friday oct 13 was just a fluke 
remains squarely on the shoulders of the bulls he asserts 
whatever the eventual outcome analysts who see the markets 
recent antics in a negative light say the prevailing optimistic 
view was selfcontradictory 
on the one hand the selloff was described as unlike the 87 
crash because it occurred in such different circumstances 
on the other it was embraced as a buying opportunity very 
similar to what occurred two years before 
either one of those interpretations could turn out to be true 
the skeptics say but not likely both 
