<TEXT>
regulators who tried to close lincoln savings 
and loan association say the thrifts millionaire owner fought back 
as late as this spring with political influence reaching the 
highest levels of government 
william j crawford commissioner of the california department 
of savings and loans told the house banking committee on thursday 
that two attempts were made from washington on behalf of phoenix 
businessman charles h keating jr to approve the sale of lincoln 
to a group of investors 
crawford never approved the sale described as a sham by 
federal regulator william black 
within weeks of the calls the irvine califbased sampl was 
taken over by the federal deposit insurance corp and is expected 
to require a 2 billion bailout making it the nations costliest 
thrift failure 
carolyn jordan an aide to sen alan cranston dcalif urged 
approval of the sale in march in april according to crawford 
sen dennis deconcini dariz called crawfords boss business 
transportation and housing secretary john geoghegan 
crawford said deconcini called at the instigation of the top 
federal thrift regulator m danny wall 
in an 8hour hearing crawford and san franciscobased 
officials of walls agency the office of thrift supervision 
detailed keatings threeyear effort to deter them from bringing 
enforcement action against his institution 
the effort included what they characterized as secret meetings 
in 1987 between keating and wall as well as the enlistment of five 
senators to plead lincolns cause and the hiring of federal reserve 
board chairman alan greenspan then a private economist as a 
consultant to defend the thrifts financial condition 
michael patriarca the thrift offices chief supervisory agent 
in san francisco and black counsel in that office had 
recommended in may 1987 that the government seize lincoln to end 
reckless activities and prevent further losses 
their recommendation was rejected and in an unprecedented move 
the case was transferred from the san francisco office to agency 
headquarters in washington patriarca and black said that delayed 
action by two years 
if our recommendations had been followed the taxpayers 
would have suffered dramatically smaller losses black said it 
need not have happened and would not have happened if regulators 
in washington had showed any backbone 
