lin broadcasting corp and bellsouth corp said 
friday they had agreed on a revised plan to merge their cellular 
telephone interests in a deal that would create the nations 
largest cellular operation 
the deal which will be presented to lin shareholders for a vote 
in december or january could prompt revision of a pending buyout 
bid for lin from mccaw cellular communications inc the current 
leader in the cellular field 
a key element of the revised plan is a boost in the special cash 
dividend lin plans to pay its shareholders before the merger to 
42 per share or 226 billion from a 20 per share under the 
initial merger plan 
lin also said it had exercised its right of first refusal to buy 
metromedia cos 46 percent interest in a cellular franchise 
serving new york city for 19 billion mccaw had bid for that 
interest but lin as the holder of most of the rest of the 
franchise had the right to match mccaws offer 
mccaw based in kirkland wash is bidding for a controlling 
interest in lin and said it was extending its offer until midnight 
nov 17 the offer had been set to expire at midnight friday 
we believe the revised bellsouth offer still raises more 
questions than it answers mccaw said in a statement it urged 
lins directors to conduct a fair auction on a level playing 
field 
analysts said they doubted the latest linbellsouth plan was the 
last word in what has become an increasingly complicated battle for 
lin 
it is difficult to compare the value of the competing plans 
patrick jurczak telecommunications analyst for merrill lynch amp 
co said he valued the linbellsouth deal at 118 a share to 120 
a share for lin stockholders compared with 113 a share under the 
latest mccaw bid 
joel gross telecommunications analyst for donaldson lufkin 
jenrette securities corp valued the bellsouth offer at 117 to 
124 a share compared with 110 to 112 a share under the mccaw 
offer 
it puts the ball back in mccaws court gross said we had 
always said this would be a multipart game 
in national overthecounter trading lin rose 462 a share to 
11262 while mccaw fell 250 a share to 3775 bellsouth fell 
87 cents a share to 5212 in trading on the new york stock 
exchange 
the battle for lin a new yorkbased cellular concern which also 
has seven television stations and a specialty publishing operation 
began in june when mccaw launched an unsolicited takeover bid 
lin rejected the offer but later agreed to merge its cellular 
operations with those of bellsouth the regional telephone company 
from atlanta that wants to extend its reach in the cellular 
business 
mccaw then revised its buyout bid and offered 125 a share for 
22 million of lins shares combined with the 51 million shares 
mccaw already owns the stake would give mccaw 503 percent of 
lins 54 million shares 
both the mccaw and the bellsouth deals contain provisions under 
which those companies could acquire the remainder of the stock in 
the cellular company several years down the road 
lin chairman and president donald a pels said friday the 
revised linbellsouth proposal is clearly superior to mccaws 
coercive twotiered offer 
the plan calls for lin and bell to merge their cellular 
operations in a new company in which lin shareholders and bellsouth 
each would have a 50 percent stake executives said the deal could 
be completed in the first quarter of 1990 after securing regulatory 
approval 
bellsouth made payment of the higher special cash dividend to 
lin shareholders possible by agreeing to contribute about 800 
million less debt to the new cellular company than originally 
envisioned 
the lin shareholders will also get stock in a new company that 
is being created by the spinoff of lins seven television stations 
lin officials valued that broadcasting company at between 12 and 
15 a share 
counting the additional interest in the new york cellular 
franchise the combination of lin and bellsouth cellular operations 
would have a potential audience of 549 million that would 
displace mccaw as the cellular leader it has interests in cellular 
companies with a potential audience of 50 million 
bellsouth said it would pay up to 10 a share in five years to 
lin shareholders who continue to hold stock in the cellular company 
if certain appraisals indicate they could done better under the 
mccaw proposal 
